patch.description:
This endpoint supports

1. <b>Modifying</b> the metadata of a household resource
2. <b>Adding</b> members to a household. In order to add a member to a household, the member should not be in another household.
3. <b>Removing</b> members from a household
4. <b>Updating</b> the household role of members

<h3>Adding, removing, or modifying a household member</h3>

Lets say we have the following request that returns an existing household

```
GET /v1/households/{household_id}?include=members

{
  "id": "household_id"
  "name": "some household name",
  ...
  "_embedded": {
    "members": [
      {
        "id": "some_profile_id",
        ...
        "household_role": "parent"
      },
      {
        "id": "some_other_profile_id",
        ...
        "household_role": "child"
      },
      {
        "id": "some_untouched_profile",
        ...
        "household_role": "child"
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

And the following update is made

```
PATCH /v1/households/{household_id}

{
  "name": "new household name",
  "_embedded": {
    "members": [
      {
        "id": "some_profile_id",
        "household_role": "guardian" // update the parent to guardian
      },
      {
        "id": "some_brand_new_profile_id", // remove the old profile and add a new one with the child role
        "household_role": "child"
      },
      {
        "id": "some_untouched_profile",
        "household_role": "child"
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

This will yield the following response

```
{
  "id": "household_id",
  "name": "new household name",
  ...
  "_embedded": {
    "members": [
      {
        "id": "some_profile_id",
        ...
        "household_role": "guardian"
      },
      {
        "id": "some_brand_new_profile_id",
        ...
        "household_role": "child"
      },
      {
        "id": "some_untouched_profile",
        ...
        "household_role": "child"
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

Summary of what happened:

1. <b>Update</b> Profile `some_profile_id` so it's `household_role` is now `guardian`.
2. <b>Remove</b> Profile `some_other_profile_id` from the household since it no longer is in the `members` array.
3. <b>Add</b> Profile `some_brand_new_profile_id` and assign it's `household_role` to be `child`.
4. <b>Update</b> the name of the household to new household name

<h4>Notes</h4>

* Updating household members acts like a PUT request. The members array in the request body will be used to update the members list in the database. The members list in the database will be overwritten with the members array in the request body. This means that any member that is not included in the request body will be removed from the household. Thus, the member with the id `some_untouched_profile` needs to be included in the request body in order to stay in the household.
* The `household_role` is <b>required</b>

<h3>Modifying Household Metadata Without Modifying Members</h3>

If a request is made where `_embedded.members` is not present in the request body, the members array will not be modified at all.

```
PATCH /v1/households/{household_id}

{
  "name": "new household name"
}
```

```
Response

{
  "name": "new household name",
  ...
  "_embedded": {
    "members": [
      {
        "id": "some_profile_id"
      },
      {
        "id": "some_brand_new_profile_id"
      },
      {
        "id": "some_untouched_profile"
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

<h3>Errors</h3>

<h4>Removing All Household Members</h4>

If the following request is made

```
PATCH /v1/households/{household_id}

{
  "_embedded": {
    "members": []
  }
}
```

Response
```
{
    "errors": [
        {
            "code": "invalid_value",
            "detail": "members must contain at least 1 member"
            "source": {
                "pointer": "/_embedded.members"
            }
        }
    ]
}
```

This endpoint will throw a validation error since the household must have at least 1 member. To remove all the members of a household, the household can be deleted instead.

<h4>Adding a Member</h4>

When adding a member to a household, the `household_role` is <b>required</b>.

Lets say we have a request where we are trying to add 2 new members to an already existing household

```
GET /v1/households/{household_id}?include=members

{
  "id": "household_id",
  "name": "new household name",
  ...
  "_embedded": {
    "members": [
      {
        "id": "some_profile_id",
        ...
        "household_role": "guardian"
      },
      {
        "id": "some_brand_new_profile_id",
        ...
        "household_role": "child"
      },
      {
        "id": "some_untouched_profile",
        ...
        "household_role": "child"
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

```
PATCH /v1/households/{household_id}

{
  "_embedded": {
    "members": [
      {
        "id": "some_other_profile_id",
        // household_role is missing
      },
      {
        "id": "some_other_profile_id_2",
        "household_role": "some invalid household role" // household_role is invalid
      },
      ...
    ]
  }
}
```

```
Response body

{
    "errors": [
        {
            "code": "missing_value",
            "detail": "household_role is required"
            "source": {
                "pointer": "/_embedded/members/0/household_role" // 0 indicates the index of the member that caused the error
            }
        },
        {
            "code": "invalid_value",
            "detail": "household_role is invalid: some invalid household role"
            "source": {
                "pointer": "/_embedded/members/1/household_role" // 1 indicates the index of the member that caused the error
            }
        }
    ]
}
```

The server will throw an error for each member that fails validation. All members must pass validation in order for the request to pass.

Also note that a new member cannot be added to a household if that member is already a guest in the same household.

<h4>Members Limit</h4>

A request that attempts to update a household so that it contains more than 20 members will return the following error

```
PATCH /v1/households/{household_id}
{
  "_embedded": {
    "members": [
      // members exceeds 20 member objects
      ...
    ]
  }
}
```

```
Response
{
    "errors": [
        {
            "code": "invalid_value",
            "detail": "members exceeds max size: 20"
            "source": {
                "pointer": "/_embedded/members"
            }
        }
    ]
}
```

<h3>Adding or Modifying the household address</h3>

There are a 2 ways to update the address of the Household.
  1. Send a Address ID. If an `_embedded.address.id` is provided, the service will attempt to look up and attach the requested address to the Household.<br />
    <b>Note</b>: The service will throw a 400 error if there is an issue linking the address to the household.

    PATCH /v1/households/{household_id}
    {
      "_embedded": {
        "address": {
          "id": "some_address_id"
        }
      }
    }

    Response
    {
      ...
      "_embedded": {
        "address": {
          "id": "some_address_id",
          "street": "some street",
          "city": "some city",
          ...
        }
      }
    }

  2. Send Address fields without an ID. If an addresses fields are populated without an ID, the service will create a new address and attach it to the Household.<br />
    <b>Note</b>: If an ID is provided with other address fields, the existing address matching the ID will overwrite any provided fields.

    PATCH /v1/households/{household_id}
    {
      "_embedded": {
        "address": {
          "street": "some street",
          "city": "some city",
          ...
        }
      }
    }

    Response
    {
      ...
      "_embedded": {
        "address": {
          "id": "some_address_id",
          "street": "some street",
          "city": "some city",
          ...
        }
      }
    }

tags.description:
There are two kinds of resources: single and collection resources.

### Single resources
A single resource is usually represented simply as a JSON object (`{}`)
with some fields. Almost all single resources have `id`, `created_at`, and
`updated_at` fields.

#### Example
```json
{
  "id": "64ca8ae1-2ed3-4ebd-ba8e-911394b4eb69"
  "foo": "bar",
  "created_at": "2019-09-02T16:38:21Z",
  "updated_at": "2019-09-04T23:39:05Z"
}
```

### Collection resources
Collection resources are objects containing an `_embedded` field that has
one field named after the type of resource it contains. This field's value
is an array of single resources. The collection resource may also have
`count` and `total` fields, where `count` is the number of resources
present in the array under `_embedded`, and `total` is the number of
resources that would appear in that array if [pagination](/#tag/Pagination)
were disregarded.

#### Example
```json
{
  "total": 45,
  "count": 3,
  "_embedded": {
    "foos": [
      {
        "id": "06002e59-8729-4af7-8dd6-1c8e9815ae3d"
      }, {
        "id": "3e6fc94e-88c9-445d-90c6-64b3d2612024"
      }, {
        "id": "2c6f2c45-a40d-4ec3-ae81-edba32c4bb94"
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

### HAL
Two parts of the HAL spec are implemented in this API: the `_links` and
`_embedded` objects. `_links` and `_embedded` are special fields that may
appear on any single or collection resource.

`_links` contains named URLs related to the current resource. A `self`
link is always included, which contains the URL of the current resource.
Collection resources may also contain links to other pages of resources.
The `_links` object may also contain URLs relevant to the resource, such
as the location of a file or another way to access a resource.

#### Example
```json
{
  "_links": {
    "self": "https://core.subsplash.com/acme/v1/widgets/99c99dd0-021f-4662-9dbe-8bf0d480929c"
  },
  "id": "99c99dd0-021f-4662-9dbe-8bf0d480929c",
  "foo": "bar"
}
```

When `_embedded` is present on a _collection_ resource, it only contains an
array field named after the type of resource being requested.

#### Example
See the example for **Collection resources** above.

When `_embedded` is present on a _single_ resource, it contains other
resources related to the current one. Which resources appear here may
often be controlled via the [`include`](/#tag/Includes) parameter.

#### Example
```json
{
  "id": "99c99dd0-021f-4662-9dbe-8bf0d480929c"
  "foo": "bar",
  "_embedded": {
    "fidgets": [
      {
        "id": "bbab2cad-54af-492e-9752-5fff79b3d275",
        "baz": "qux"
      },
      {
        "id": "bbab2cad-54af-492e-9752-5fff79b3d275",
        "baz: "bar"
      }
    ],
    "gadget": {
      "id": "00fd3755-f6df-4230-9680-32f821eff0d2",
      "bar": "baz"
    }
  }
}
```

Notably, CURIEs are not implemented by this API.
